<section class="min-vh-100 bg-dark-pink">
  <div class="container">
     <div class="row align-items-center py-3 mx-5">
       <%= image_tag("patched-planting.png", alt: "Patched planting screen", class: "col-12 col-md-4 py-3") %>
       <%= image_tag("patched-home-screen.png", alt: "Patched home screen", class: "col-12 col-md-4 py-3") %>
       <%= image_tag("patched-setup-screen.png", alt: "Patched set-up screen", class: "col-12 col-md-4 py-3") %>
     </div>
  </div>
</section>

<section class="min-vh-100 bg-gray alignment">
  <div class="align-items-center pb-5 pt-5">
    <div class="container">
      <h6 class="pt-3">The challenge</h6>
      <h1 class="pb-5">Design and code a Ruby on Rails web app for mobile as a team of four.</h1>
    </div>
      <div class="container">
        <div class="row">
          <div class="col-sm-12 col-md-4 pb-3">
            <h6>Background</h6>
            <p>The brief was to create a Ruby on Rails web app from scratch. I pitched the idea for an eco gardening app and my teammates voted to work on it with me.</p>
            <p>We had a day of class-time to hash out the product design, plus evenings and weekends to refine the details, then we coded the app in 8 days.</p>
          </div>
            <div class="col-sm-12 col-md-4 pb-3">
              <h6>The outcome</h6>
              <p>A functioning web app for mobile which provides a simple step-by-step guide for setup, planting, care and harvesting.</p>
              <p>The app shows you which vegetables to plant and harvest and when, depending on the user’s garden’s specifications.</p>
            </div>
              <div class="col-sm-12 col-md-4 pb-3">
                <h6>Team</h6>
                <p class="pb-3">Patrícia Amaral Nunes, Luís Vaz Pinto, Mariana Saavedra, Louise Hill</p>
                <h6>Role</h6>
                <p class="pb-3">Concept, UX design, UI design Front-end and back-end development</p>
                <h6>Project type</h6>
                <p class="pb-3">Student, concept @ Le Wagon</p>
              </div>
        </div>
          <%= link_to "#" do %>
          <span>
          <h6 class="link-external">The code on Github
          <%= image_tag("arrow-up-right.svg", alt: "Link arrow", class: "up-arrow") %>
          </h6>
          </span>
          <% end %>
          <%= link_to "#" do %>
          <span>
          <h6 class="link-external">Patched app on mobile
          <%= image_tag("arrow-up-right.svg", alt: "Link arrow", class: "up-arrow") %>
          </h6>
          </span>
          <% end %>
      </div>
  </div>
</section>

<section>
  <%= image_tag("patched-tote-bag.png", alt: "Tote bag saying - here for you from planting to plate", class: "w-100") %>
</section>

<section class="min-vh-100 bg-light-pink alignment">
  <div class="container">
    <div class="row">
      <div class="col-sm-12 col-md-6">
        <h1 class="pb-3">“Most of the gardening blogs and websites did not provide the right information, or communicated it in very complicated terms”</h1>
        <p class="pb-3"><u>
          <%= link_to "plantedwell.com", "#", class: "desc-link"  %></u>
      </div>
        <div class="col-sm-12 col-md-6">
          <p>I had an afternoon to come up with an app idea so I interviewed a friend. He is an organic gardening enthusiast and opened my eyes to the difficulties of keeping away pests without using harmful chemicals.</p>
          <p>I spoke to a few friends who have recently bought their first house and asked them about their gardens. What jumped out was an enthusiasm for eco-friendly gardening, but uncertainty around how to actually get started. A quick google highlighted a problem in tracking down clear gardening information for beginners.</p>
        </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<section class="min-vh-100 bg-light-pink">
  <div class="container pt-5">
    <div class="row align-items-center py-3 mx-5">
      <%= image_tag("vegetable-selection.png", alt: "Vegetable selection screen", class: "col-12 col-md-4 py-3") %>
      <%= image_tag("watering-care-screen.png", alt: "Tips on how to water the patch", class: "col-12 col-md-4 py-3") %>
      <%= image_tag("harvest-screen.png", alt: "Vegetable harvest screen", class: "col-12 col-md-4 py-3") %>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<section class="min-vh-100 bg-light-pink alignment">
  <div class="container">
    <div class="row">
      <div class="col-sm-12 col-md-6 pb-3">
        <h1 class="pb-1">“Almost 3 million new gardening projects in the last year, nearly half of new gardeners under 45”</h1>
        <p class="quote pb-3">
        <u><%= link_to "hortweek.com", "#", class: "desc-link" %>
        </u>
      </div>
        <div class="col-sm-12 col-md-6 pb-3">
          <p>Research showed a huge boost in gardening during the Corona pandemic, especially amongst under 45s. The<u> 
          <%= link_to "HTA Garden Retail Monitor", "#", class: "desc-link" %>
          </u>found that sales of gardening products were up 34%, 17% and 19% in June, July and August respectively in UK garden centres in 2020, compared to 2019. On average, individual customers were spending 35% more on gardening products. In fact, the<u>
          <%= link_to "Royal Horticultural Society", "#", class: "desc-link" %>
          </u>believes gardening is entering a new “golden age”.</p>
          <p>And what about eco-gardening?<u>
          <%= link_to "67% of UK gardeners", "#", class: "desc-link" %>
          </u>say they’re eco-conscious and 46% of this group already use organic fertilisers.<u>
          <%= link_to "The 2021 Organic Market Report", "#", class: "desc-link" %>
          </u>revealed the highest year-on-year growth in 15 years for the organic market, at +12.6%, with the market now worth £2.79B.</p>
        </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<section>
  <%= image_tag("tomatoes-planting.png", alt: "Patched tomato planting screen", class: "w-100") %>
</section>

<section class="min-vh-100 bg-gray alignment">
  <div class="container">
    <div class="row">
      <div class="col-sm-12 col-md-6 pb-3">
        <h1 class="pb-1">“There is considerable evidence that 120 minutes’ exposure to nature a week is a key factor in maintaining positive mental health.”</h1>
        <p class="quote pt-3">Dr Alan Kellas, Green Care Lead, Royal College of Psychiatrists</p>
        <p><u>
          <%= link_to "theguardian.com", "#", class: "desc-link" %>
          </u></p>
      </div>
        <div class="col-sm-12 col-md-6 pb-3">
          <p>The mental health benefits of gardening have been widely documented. A huge study by the<u>
          <%= link_to "University of Exeter", "#", class: "desc-link" %>
          </u>on gardens and gardening showed that people who spent time in the garden report better physical and mental health levels than those who do not.</p>
          <p><u>
          <%= link_to "The eco plusses of gardening are also considerable", "#", class: "desc-link" %>
          </u>—from supporting beneficial insects and birds, to reducing the carbon footprint of home-grown food, to increasing oxygen in the air.</p>
          <p>As a team we decided on what was feasible to build in the timeframe and focused on growing vegetables so there would be a delicious reward at the end of each growing cycle.</p>
        </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

